    "153988008": {
      "title": "Corporate growth and diversification",
      "abstract": "THE rise to a position of dominance of the conglomerate merger is one of the more striking features of contemporary industrial organization.' The term conglomerate implies that the resulting firm is more broadly diversified than the merging partners, and there is at least the suggestion that these (conglomerate) firms are more broadly diversified than other manufacturing firms of comparable size. There is also a general presumption that industrial diversification by all large manufacturing firms has recently been on the increase.2"
